SIMPLE: serious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Serious
<hw>Se"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>serius</ets>: cf. F. <ets>s⟦eacute⟧rieux</ets>, LL.
<ets>seriosus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Grave in manner or
disposition; earnest; thoughtful; solemn; not light, gay, or
volatile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is always <qex>serious</qex>, yet there is about his manner a
graceful ease.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Really intending what is said; being in earnest; not
jesting or deceiving.</def> <rj><au>Beaconsfield.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Important; weighty; not trifling; grave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The holy Scriptures bring to our ears the most <qex>serious</qex>
things in the world.</q> <rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence, giving rise to apprehension; attended with
danger; <as>as, a <ex>serious</ex> injury</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Grave; solemn; earnest; sedate; important;
weighty. See <er>Grave</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Se"ri*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Se"ri*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seriph</ent>⟦br⟧
